{
  "doc_id": "2586",
  "text": "Following transplantation, islets undergo apoptosis and necrosis from transient local hypoxia, a lack of nutrient support [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , and hyperglycemia-induced toxicity [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . While use of fibroblast growth factor-2 (FGF-2) at the time of transplantation improves revascularization of islet grafts and facilitates their engraftment [CITATION_5] , this approach addresses only part of the problem. Collagenase digestion of the pancreas has been shown to induce apoptosis of isolated islets from anoikis and loss of cell-matrix interactions [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . In addition, islets express proinflammatory nuclear factor-B (NF-B)-dependent genes after isolation, amplifying apoptosis signaling and potentially inducing immunological rejection (14 -16) . Optimization of the isolation process to reduce islet stress has failed to improve recovery, leaving uncontrolled apoptosis as the main cause of poor islet yield [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] .",
